The current literature suggests that remote teams may face challenges in adapting to new work environments, including lower productivity levels during the initial adaptation period. However, the evidence is not yet conclusive, and more research is needed to establish the relationships between various factors and productivity outcomes among remote teams.

Three hypotheses related to remote team productivity were evaluated based on the input: Productivity Decline, Communication Breakdown, and Difficulty in Establishing Routine. While some evidence was presented to support these hypotheses, additional research would be necessary to provide concrete conclusions about their robustness and causal relationships.

In particular, effective managerial support, including regular check-ins and clear communication, appears to positively impact the productivity of remote teams. In contrast, autocratic management styles may negatively impact productivity outcomes. The relationship between team experience, technology utilization, and individual motivation is also an important consideration in determining the effectiveness of different management styles for promoting productivity among remote teams.

Future research should focus on gathering more robust data on remote team productivity during the initial adaptation period, as well as examining the relationships between various factors and productivity outcomes. By building on existing knowledge and identifying areas for further investigation, researchers can work towards developing evidence-based strategies for enhancing productivity in remote teams.
